Simulation and distributions¶

In order to understand how the correlation between the inputs impacts the standard error on the regression coefficients, we need to find some data! Although we could find real data to work with, we can also simulate data! This way we are in control of the assumptions and we will know everything there is to know about the data.

Let's start out with a simple case where the inputs are not correlated. We will assume that both inputs have marginal standard normal distributions. Thus, they each have mean equal to 0 and standard deviation equal to 1. We can generate random values for the inputs by calling a Gaussian random number generator. However, we want to expand our example to a setting where the inputs are correlated. Thus, we will work with the more general multivariate normal (MVN) distribution. The MVN is a distribution that describes the central tendancy of a collection of variables, their uncertainty, and how they relate to each other or their covariance. The general notation for the MVN for $D$ variables, $\mathbf{x}=x_1, x_2, ..., x_d, ..., x_D$:

$$\mathbf{x} \mid \boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \sim \mathrm{multivariate \, normal} \left(\mathbf{x} \mid \boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right) $$

In the above expression, $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is the mean vector, and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is the covariance matrix. Let's focus on our specific case where we have 2 inputs, thus our mean vector will be $(2\times1)$ and our covariance matrix will be $(2\times2)$.

$$\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} \sim \mathrm{multivariate \, normal} \left( \begin{bmatrix} \mu_1 \\ \mu_2 \end{bmatrix} , \begin{bmatrix} \mathrm{var}(x_1) & \mathrm{cov}(x_1, x_2) \\ \mathrm{cov}(x_2, x_1) & \mathrm{var}(x_2) \end{bmatrix} \right)$$

The MVN can be simplified by writing the covariance in terms of the marginal standard deviations for each input $\sigma_1$, $\sigma_2$ and the correlation coefficient, $\rho$, between them:

$$\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} \sim \mathrm{multivariate \, normal} \left( \begin{bmatrix} \mu_1 \\ \mu_2 \end{bmatrix} , \begin{bmatrix} \sigma_1^2 & \rho \sigma_1 \sigma_2 \\ \rho \sigma_1 \sigma_2 & \sigma_2^2 \end{bmatrix} \right)$$

By assuming each input has a marginal standard normal distribution, each input has means of 0, $\mu_1 =\mu_2 = 0$, and standard deviations equal to 1, $\sigma_1 = \sigma_2 = 1$. The MVN distribution simplifies considerably:

$$\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} \sim \mathrm{multivariate \, normal} \left( \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} , \begin{bmatrix} 1 & \rho \\ \rho & 1 \end{bmatrix} \right)$$

Now, when we consider our starting case of uncorrelated inputs, the correlation coefficient is equal to 0, $\rho = 0$. The multivariate normal has simplified even further, the covariance matrix is just the identity matrix:

$$\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} \sim \mathrm{multivariate \, normal} \left( \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} , \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \right)$$

The above distribution is equivalent to two independent standard normals:

$$x_1 \sim \mathrm{normal}\left(x_1 \mid 0, 1 \right)$$

$$x_2 \sim \mathrm{normla}\left(x_2 \mid 0, 1 \right)$$

Again we are working with the general multivariate case so it is easier to expand to correlated inputs later.

Now that we know what distribution to use, it's time to generate random observations! Let's follow the same approach we used at the start of the semester where we import the necessary modules then initialize the NumPy random number generator object.

Regression coefficient calculations¶

Great! We just generated our inputs! How can calculate standard errors on the coefficients of our linear model? We do not have any responses!

The covariance matrix of the $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ parameters is only influenced by the response, $\mathbf{y}$, via the residual error, $\hat{\sigma}$. The covariance structure is completely determined by the covariance structure of the inputs! Thus, we can completely study the uncertainty and relationship between the parameters without having any values for the response!

We need to organize the inputs properly though to support our calculations. We must create the design matrix, $\mathbf{X}$. The design matrix will depend on our model formulation, our desired set of features. For our current application, we are working with linear additive features:

$$\mu_n = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{n,1} + \beta_2 x_{n,2}$$

Let's use dmatrix() to create the design matrix for us. The dmatrix() function is the sister function to dmatrices(). The dmatrix() function only generates the design matrix or input feature array. It does not generate the output array.

In [11]:
from patsy import dmatrix
In [12]:
X_rho_zero = dmatrix( ' ~ x01 + x02', data = xinputs_rho_zero_df)
In [13]:
print( type(X_rho_zero) )

print( X_rho_zero.shape )

(100, 3)

Looking at the head of our design matrix shows the "intercept column of 1's"!

pd.DataFrame(X_rho_zero).head()

Let's now calculate the matrix sum of squares using our randomly generated input values. The number of rows and columns of the matrix sum of squares is equal to the number of columns in the design matrix! Several linear algebra related functions are required to execute the calculations. The cell below uses the np.dot() function and the .T attribute to matrix multiply the transpose of the design matrix with itself.

In [15]:
SSmat_rho_zero = np.dot( X_rho_zero.T, X_rho_zero )
In [16]:
print( SSmat_rho_zero )

[[100.          -0.15922493  -1.67926222]
 [ -0.15922493  88.93157023  -5.17180241]
 [ -1.67926222  -5.17180241  83.98430012]]

The scaled covariance matrix between the $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ parameter is then the inverse of the matrix sum of squares. We will refer to this as the scaled covariance matrix, because we are essentially ignoring the residual error. Large values of the residual error will increase the standard error of the coefficients even further. The np.linalg.inv() function is used to invert the matrix sum of squares below.

In [19]:
beta_cov_rho_zero = np.linalg.inv( SSmat_rho_zero )
In [20]:
print( beta_cov_rho_zero )

[[1.00034367e-02 2.96485713e-05 2.01844033e-04]
 [2.96485713e-05 1.12851026e-02 6.95536053e-04]
 [2.01844033e-04 6.95536053e-04 1.19538547e-02]]

The standard errors of three $\beta$ parameters are the square root of the terms along the main diagonal.

In [21]:
np.sqrt( np.diag( beta_cov_rho_zero) )
Out[21]:
array([0.10001718, 0.10623136, 0.10933369])

The standard errors on the slopes $\beta_1$ and $\beta_2$ have essentially doubled! The potential impact of this is that the highly correlated inputs have made it more difficult to know if one of the two inputs is statistically significant or not!

Let's check the correlation coefficient between $\beta_1$ and $\beta_2$. The definition for the correlation coefficient is:

$$\rho = \frac{\mathrm{cov}\left(x_1, x_2\right)}{\sigma_1 \sigma_2} $$

Let's define a function to help us calculate it. The first argument to calc_cor_coef() is the covariance matrix. The second argument is the index i and the third argument is the index j. Thus, the function calculates the correlation coefficient between the i and j terms in the covariance matrix.

In [30]:
def calc_cor_coef(Cmat, i, j):
    sv = np.sqrt( np.diag(Cmat) )
    
    cov_ij = Cmat[i, j]
    
    return cov_ij / (sv[i] * sv[j])

The correlation between $\beta_1$ and $\beta_2$ is therefore:

In [31]:
calc_cor_coef(beta_cov_rho_high, 1, 2)
Out[31]:
-0.907732608525123

Thus, highly positive correlation in the inputs becomes highly negative correlation of the coefficients!

Monte Carlo simulation study¶

We practiced generating random inputs, and calculated the regression coefficient covariance, for a few values of the input correlation. However, we generated just a single random draw for each value of the correlation coefficient. How repeatable are our calculations? What if the inputs change slightly, we will still have the same conclusions?

To test this, we will repeat the simulations multiple times for each input correlation coefficient. Thus, instead of just generating 1 set of 100 input observations, we will generate 10 sets of 100 input observations. For each set, we will calculate the coefficient standard errors and the correlation coefficient between $\beta_1$ and $\beta_2$.

Also, instead of just using 3 values for the input correlation coefficient, we will try out many values for $\rho$. We will consider values of from -.99 to 0.99 in increments of 0.01.

Let's define functions to help us perform this simulation study. For simplicity we will assume there are just 2 inputs and we are using linear additive features in our model.

To allow some generality the sim_generate_design() function allows the user to provide non-zero means and marginal standard deviations different from one. Thus, sim_generate_design() works with the more general multivariate normal distribution:

$$\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} \sim \mathrm{multivariate \, normal} \left( \begin{bmatrix} \mu_1 \\ \mu_2 \end{bmatrix} , \begin{bmatrix} \sigma_1^2 & \rho \sigma_1 \sigma_2 \\ \rho \sigma_1 \sigma_2 & \sigma_2^2 \end{bmatrix} \right)$$
In [40]:
def sim_generate_design(rho, xmu, xsd, num_samples):
    xcov_val = rho * xsd[0] * xsd[1]
    
    xcovmat = np.array([[xsd[0], xcov_val], [xcov_val, xsd[1]]])
    
    xinputs = rg.multivariate_normal(xmu, xcovmat, size=num_samples)
    
    xdf = pd.DataFrame(xinputs, columns=['x'+str(d+1).zfill(2) for d in range(xinputs.shape[1])])
    
    X = dmatrix( ' ~ x01 + x02', data = xdf)
    
    return X

The calc_lm_expressions() function calculates the covariance matrix for the $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ parameters for a given design matrix X.

In [41]:
def calc_lm_expressions(X):
    SSmat = np.dot( X.T, X )
    
    beta_covmat = np.linalg.inv( SSmat )
    
    return beta_covmat

The sim_replicate() function performs one replication of our study. It generates 1 set of a specified number of observations of the inputs, and calculates the coefficient standard errors and the correlation coefficient between $\beta_1$ and $\beta_2$. A DataFrame is returned to facilitate making figures later.

In [42]:
def sim_replicate(rep_id, rho, xmu, xsd, N):
    Xmat = sim_generate_design(rho, xmu, xsd, N)
    
    bmat = calc_lm_expressions(Xmat)
    
    bse = np.sqrt( np.diag(bmat) )
    
    rho12 = calc_cor_coef(bmat, 1, 2)
    
    res = pd.DataFrame({'rep_id': rep_id,
                        'rho': rho,
                        'b0_se': bse[0],
                        'b1_se': bse[1],
                        'b2_se': bse[2],
                        'cor_b1_b2': rho12},
                       index=[rep_id])
    
    return res

Although we could use different values for the marginal means and standard deviations, we will continue to use marginal standard normals. Let's test out our function and confirm we get roughly the same result as we got with the highly positively correlated inputs.

In [43]:
x_mean_vector = np.zeros(2)

x_sd_vector = np.ones(2)

sim_replicate(1, 0.9, x_mean_vector, x_sd_vector, 100)

We will use a simple nested for-loop to loop over the desired values for the correlation coefficient and the desired number of replications for each value of $\rho$. We will create a NumPy 1D array between -0.99 to 0.99 in increments (step size) of 0.01 with the np.arange() function. The number of replications are created simply with range(10) since we want to use 10 replications for each correlation coefficient.

In [44]:
rho_use = np.arange(-0.99, 1.0, 0.01) #np.arange() stop is exclusive...

reps_use = range(10)

res_list = []

for rho_v in rho_use:
    for rid in reps_use:
        res_list.append( sim_replicate(rid, rho_v, x_mean_vector, x_sd_vector, 100))

Let's now use Seaborn to visualize the average and $\pm$ 1 standard deviation interval around the average (so not the confidence interval on the average) for the standard errors with respect to the input correlation coefficient.

In [52]:
sns.relplot(data = sim_study_slope_se, x='rho', y='value', kind='line', errorbar='sd', col='variable')

plt.show()

When the input correlation is relatively low, $-0.5 < \rho < 0.5$, the standard error on the coefficients is roughly the same value as if the inputs were uncorrelated, $\rho=0$. However, the standard errors start to increase for $0.5 < |\rho| < 0.85$. Then, the standard errors increase essentially exponentially when $|\rho| > 0.85$.

This is why the usual recommendation is that if your inputs are correlated with correlation coefficients of greater than 0.85 or less than -0.85 model interpretation will be impacted! The regression coefficients will be correlated which raises the uncertainty on the regression coefficients!

Summary¶

This notebook involved more math than most examples this semester. The primary point is that we used random number generators to demonstrate an important concept about model behavior. Randomly generating data can therefore help us understand how models work!
